	<article>

		<header>
			
			<h1>Namibian president calls for waiving of EPA deadline </h1>

			
			<h4>
												16 September 2012
										</h4>

					</header>


		
		
					<p>According to Namibian press reports, at the end of July 2012, President Pohamba of Namibia called on the EU to waive the 1 January 2014 deadline for the conclusion of the EPA negotiations process. It was estimated in a report that, under current EC proposals, if the EPA negotiations were not completed by that date then import duties of ‘more than N$600 million’ (approx. €55.7m) would be imposed on Namibian goods imported into the EU (based on 2009 trade volumes).</p><p>The Namibian government has been lobbying EU institutions for some time to either abandon or extend the EC’s proposed deadline, including through direct representations to EU member state governments. In June 2012, the International Trade Committee of the European Parliament voted by 25 votes to 2 (with two abstentions) to extend until 1 January 2016 the 2014 deadline proposed by the Commission. Namibian Parliamentary representatives to the ACP–EU Joint Parliamentary Assembly argued ‘things are moving in the right direction’. This followed earlier insistence on the part of the EP Development Committee that ‘the conclusion of the negotiations should be driven by content, which must take into account the interests and address the concerns of both parties, and not by timeframes’ .</p><p>In June 2012, the ACP Council meeting in Vanuatu rejected the EC’s reasoning behind establishing an arbitrary deadline for the EPA negotiations, and called for the negotiations to be allowed to continue until a ‘mutually beneficial’ agreement was reached. The Council called on the EC ‘to lower its ambitions and consider seriously the level of economic development of its ACP negotiating partners, with a view to concluding an inclusive EPA that will attract … all states in a given region [to sign up to it]’.</p><p>In July, President Pohamba called for the EPA negotiations to retain their development character and not give rise to a situation ‘where SADC member states would be economically disadvantaged’.</p><p>Against this background, the results of a Namibian beef sector market diversification study were also released in July 2012, with 12 potential alternative markets to the EU being identified for Namibian beef products. However, the study did not go into detail on the likely profitability of these markets.</p><p>Also in the beef sector, it was announced, meanwhile, that the Botswana Meat Corporation (BMC) had just been relisted as being able to export to the EU, although the BMC continues to seek alternative export markets in ‘the DRC, Angola and other African countries including Zimbabwe’ (where payment difficulties are hindering exports). A proposal has been tabled to open up export licensing for beef and beef products beyond the BMC, although the agriculture minister denied that this was a prelude to privatisation of BMC, pointing out that the review of public enterprises was a quite separate process. He reaffirmed his commitment to avoiding Botswana becoming simply ‘a grazing ground for feedlots in South Africa’.</p>
		
		
