				<div class="box">
			<h3>Editorial comment</h3>
			<p>Many of the EPA provisions, about which the Namibian authorities have expressed concerns since November 2007, relate to the use of trade policy tools for the promotion of agro-food sector development, particularly the use of tools permitted under SACU rules that are designed to foster more balanced regional agro-industrial development. The impact that EPA provisions would have on the use of these tools is in many instances an issue not in Namibia–EU trade, but rather in Namibia–South Africa trade.</p><p>The Namibian authorities have consistently argued since 2007 for EPA provisions to be modified to accommodate these regional agro-food sector trade realities, with efforts continuing to establish revised wording that would fully address Namibian concerns. It is against a background of the failure to finalise the process since December 2007 that the Namibian government is concerned about a deadline for the conclusion of negotiations that is less than 18 months away.</p><p>This accounts for continuing efforts in the region to identify alternative markets for those products that would be worst affected by the imposition of, in the case of Namibia, MFN duties.</p><p>In Botswana, the liberalisation of beef sector export arrangements could well help to identify a range of non-traditional markets for which access requirements are more consistent with the volatile disease status of Botswanan beef production zones.</p>
		</div>
		
